---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout 
  title="Linux I/O Models: From Blocking to io_uring" 
  description="Interactive visualization of Linux I/O models — blocking, non-blocking, epoll, io_uring, and the reactor pattern"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: "Home", href: "/" }, 
    { label: "Linux", href: "/linux/" },
    { label: "I/O Models", href: "/linux/io-models/" }
  ]}
>
  <div class="viz-container">
    <header class="viz-header">
      <h1>🐧 Linux I/O Models</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">From Blocking Sockets to io_uring — How Linux Handles Concurrent Connections</p>
    </header>

    <!-- Overview -->
    <section class="overview-section">
      <div class="overview-card">
        <p>
          Every network server must answer one question: <strong>how do you handle thousands of
          connections simultaneously?</strong> Linux has evolved through four generations of I/O models.
          <em>Blocking I/O</em> dedicates a thread per connection — simple but wasteful.
          <em>Non-blocking I/O</em> with poll/select avoids threads but burns CPU.
          <em>epoll</em> gives O(1) event notification — the foundation of Redis, Nginx, and Node.js.
          <em>io_uring</em> goes further: zero-copy, kernel-side polling, and shared ring buffers
          that eliminate syscall overhead entirely.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Scalability Comparison -->
    <section class="compare-section">
      <h2>📊 Scalability Comparison</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Drag the slider to see how each I/O model handles increasing connection counts.</p>

      <div class="slider-control">
        <label>Concurrent Connections: <strong id="connLabel">100</strong></label>
        <input type="range" id="connSlider" min="10" max="10000" value="100" step="10" class="slider">
        <div class="slider-marks">
          <span>10</span><span>1K</span><span>5K</span><span>10K</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="compare-grid">
        <div class="model-card" id="blockingCard">
          <h3>🧵 Blocking I/O</h3>
          <div class="model-metric">
            <span class="metric-label">Threads needed</span>
            <span class="metric-value" id="blockingThreads">100</span>
          </div>
          <div class="model-metric">
            <span class="metric-label">Memory overhead</span>
            <span class="metric-value" id="blockingMem">100 MB</span>
          </div>
          <div class="model-metric">
            <span class="metric-label">Context switches/s</span>
            <span class="metric-value" id="blockingSwitches">~5,000</span>
          </div>
          <div class="model-bar">
            <div class="bar-fill blocking-fill" id="blockingBar" style="width: 10%"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="model-verdict" id="blockingVerdict">Works fine</div>
        </div>

        <div class="model-card" id="epollCard">
          <h3>⚡ epoll</h3>
          <div class="model-metric">
            <span class="metric-label">Threads needed</span>
            <span class="metric-value" id="epollThreads">1-4</span>
          </div>
          <div class="model-metric">
            <span class="metric-label">Memory overhead</span>
            <span class="metric-value" id="epollMem">~1 MB</span>
          </div>
          <div class="model-metric">
            <span class="metric-label">Syscalls/event</span>
            <span class="metric-value" id="epollSyscalls">1</span>
          </div>
          <div class="model-bar">
            <div class="bar-fill epoll-fill" id="epollBar" style="width: 5%"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="model-verdict" id="epollVerdict">Excellent</div>
        </div>

        <div class="model-card" id="iouringCard">
          <h3>💎 io_uring</h3>
          <div class="model-metric">
            <span class="metric-label">Threads needed</span>
            <span class="metric-value" id="iouringThreads">1</span>
          </div>
          <div class="model-metric">
            <span class="metric-label">Memory overhead</span>
            <span class="metric-value" id="iouringMem">~0.5 MB</span>
          </div>
          <div class="model-metric">
            <span class="metric-label">Syscalls/event</span>
            <span class="metric-value" id="iouringSyscalls">0 (polled)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="model-bar">
            <div class="bar-fill iouring-fill" id="iouringBar" style="width: 3%"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="model-verdict" id="iouringVerdict">Optimal</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Blocking I/O -->
    <section class="detail-section">
      <h2>🧵 Blocking I/O: Thread Per Connection</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">The simplest model: one thread waits on each connection. When data arrives, the thread wakes up. Simple, but each thread costs ~1MB stack + kernel scheduling overhead.</p>

      <div class="blocking-viz" id="blockingViz">
        <div class="blocking-server">
          <div class="server-label">Server Process</div>
          <div class="thread-pool" id="threadPool">
            <!-- rendered by JS -->
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="blocking-clients">
          <div class="client-label">Clients</div>
          <div class="client-list" id="blockingClients">
            <!-- rendered by JS -->
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="blocking-controls">
        <button class="action-btn primary-btn" id="addClientBtn">+ Add Connection</button>
        <button class="action-btn chaos-btn" id="floodBtn">🌊 Flood (20 connections)</button>
        <button class="action-btn reset-btn" id="blockingResetBtn">🔄 Reset</button>
      </div>

      <div class="code-block">
        <div class="code-title">Thread-per-connection server (simplified)</div>
        <pre><code set:html={`while (true) {
    int client_fd = accept(server_fd, ...);  // blocks until new connection
    pthread_create(&thread, NULL, handle_client, client_fd);
}

void* handle_client(int fd) {
    char buf[4096];
    while ((n = read(fd, buf, sizeof(buf))) > 0) {  // blocks until data
        write(fd, response, resp_len);                // blocks until sent
    }
    close(fd);
}`} /></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- epoll -->
    <section class="detail-section">
      <h2>⚡ epoll: Event-Driven I/O Multiplexing</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">A single thread monitors thousands of file descriptors. The kernel tells you exactly which ones are ready — no polling, no wasted threads.</p>

      <div class="epoll-viz">
        <div class="epoll-components">
          <div class="epoll-instance">
            <div class="epoll-header">epoll instance (kernel)</div>
            <div class="epoll-interest" id="epollInterest">
              <div class="interest-label">Interest List (red-black tree)</div>
              <div class="interest-fds" id="interestFds">
                <!-- rendered by JS -->
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="epoll-ready" id="epollReady">
              <div class="ready-label">Ready List (linked list)</div>
              <div class="ready-fds" id="readyFds">
                <!-- rendered by JS -->
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="epoll-thread">
            <div class="thread-label">Event Loop Thread</div>
            <div class="epoll-loop" id="epollLoop">
              <div class="loop-step" id="loopWait">epoll_wait() — sleeping</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="epoll-controls">
          <button class="action-btn primary-btn" id="epollAddBtn">+ Register FD</button>
          <button class="action-btn election-btn" id="epollDataBtn">📨 Data Arrives</button>
          <button class="action-btn election-btn" id="epollWaitBtn">⏰ epoll_wait()</button>
          <button class="action-btn reset-btn" id="epollResetBtn">🔄 Reset</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="et-lt-section">
        <h3>Edge-Triggered vs Level-Triggered</h3>
        <div class="et-lt-grid">
          <div class="et-lt-card">
            <h4>Level-Triggered (default)</h4>
            <p>epoll_wait() returns <strong>every time</strong> you call it while the fd is ready. Like checking "is the buffer non-empty?" each time. Safer but can cause redundant wake-ups.</p>
            <div class="trigger-viz" id="ltViz">
              <div class="trigger-signal">Buffer: ████░░░░</div>
              <div class="trigger-events">
                <span class="trigger-event active">wake</span>
                <span class="trigger-event active">wake</span>
                <span class="trigger-event active">wake</span>
              </div>
              <div class="trigger-note">Keeps notifying while data present</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="et-lt-card highlight-card">
            <h4>Edge-Triggered (EPOLLET)</h4>
            <p>epoll_wait() returns <strong>only once</strong> when state changes (new data arrives). You must drain the buffer completely with non-blocking reads. Used by Nginx for performance.</p>
            <div class="trigger-viz" id="etViz">
              <div class="trigger-signal">Buffer: ████░░░░</div>
              <div class="trigger-events">
                <span class="trigger-event active">wake</span>
                <span class="trigger-event dim">—</span>
                <span class="trigger-event dim">—</span>
              </div>
              <div class="trigger-note">Notifies once per state change</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="code-block">
        <div class="code-title">epoll event loop</div>
        <pre><code set:html={`int epfd = epoll_create1(0);                    // create epoll instance
struct epoll_event ev = { .events = EPOLLIN };
ev.data.fd = server_fd;
epoll_ctl(epfd, EPOLL_CTL_ADD, server_fd, &ev); // register interest

struct epoll_event events[1024];
while (true) {
    int n = epoll_wait(epfd, events, 1024, -1);  // block until ready
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (events[i].data.fd == server_fd)
            accept_new_client(epfd);              // register new fd
        else
            handle_data(events[i].data.fd);       // read/write ready fd
    }
}`} /></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- io_uring -->
    <section class="detail-section">
      <h2>💎 io_uring: Zero-Syscall Async I/O</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Introduced in Linux 5.1. Two shared ring buffers between user and kernel space — submit operations without syscalls, reap completions without context switches.</p>

      <div class="iouring-viz">
        <div class="ring-container">
          <div class="ring-side">
            <div class="ring-label">Submission Queue (SQ)</div>
            <div class="ring-visual" id="sqRing">
              <!-- rendered by JS -->
            </div>
            <div class="ring-info">
              <span class="ring-stat">Head: <strong id="sqHead">0</strong></span>
              <span class="ring-stat">Tail: <strong id="sqTail">0</strong></span>
              <span class="ring-stat">Entries: <strong id="sqCount">0</strong>/8</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ring-arrow">
            <div class="arrow-label">Kernel processes SQEs</div>
            <div class="arrow-body">→→→</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ring-side">
            <div class="ring-label">Completion Queue (CQ)</div>
            <div class="ring-visual" id="cqRing">
              <!-- rendered by JS -->
            </div>
            <div class="ring-info">
              <span class="ring-stat">Head: <strong id="cqHead">0</strong></span>
              <span class="ring-stat">Tail: <strong id="cqTail">0</strong></span>
              <span class="ring-stat">Entries: <strong id="cqCount">0</strong>/8</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="iouring-flow">
          <div class="flow-step">
            <span class="flow-num">1</span>
            <span class="flow-text">App writes SQE to submission ring (no syscall)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flow-step">
            <span class="flow-num">2</span>
            <span class="flow-text">Kernel polls SQ or app calls io_uring_enter()</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flow-step">
            <span class="flow-num">3</span>
            <span class="flow-text">Kernel executes I/O and writes CQE to completion ring</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flow-step">
            <span class="flow-num">4</span>
            <span class="flow-text">App reads CQE from completion ring (no syscall)</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="iouring-controls">
          <button class="action-btn primary-btn" id="sqSubmitBtn">📤 Submit SQE</button>
          <button class="action-btn election-btn" id="kernelProcessBtn">⚙️ Kernel Process</button>
          <button class="action-btn election-btn" id="cqReapBtn">📥 Reap CQE</button>
          <button class="action-btn reset-btn" id="iouringResetBtn">🔄 Reset</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="code-block">
        <div class="code-title">io_uring basics</div>
        <pre><code set:html={`struct io_uring ring;
io_uring_queue_init(256, &ring, 0);           // setup rings

// Submit a read operation (no syscall!)
struct io_uring_sqe *sqe = io_uring_get_sqe(&ring);
io_uring_prep_read(sqe, fd, buf, len, 0);
sqe->user_data = (uint64_t)fd;               // tag for completion
io_uring_submit(&ring);                       // one syscall for N ops

// Reap completions
struct io_uring_cqe *cqe;
io_uring_wait_cqe(&ring, &cqe);              // wait for completion
int result = cqe->res;                        // bytes read or error
io_uring_cqe_seen(&ring, cqe);               // advance CQ head`} /></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Reactor Pattern -->
    <section class="detail-section">
      <h2>🔄 The Reactor Pattern</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">The design pattern behind Redis, Nginx, Node.js, and most high-performance servers. One event loop, many handlers.</p>

      <div class="reactor-viz">
        <div class="reactor-diagram">
          <div class="reactor-demux">
            <div class="demux-label">Event Demultiplexer</div>
            <div class="demux-sub">(epoll / kqueue / io_uring)</div>
          </div>

          <div class="reactor-loop-box">
            <div class="loop-label">Event Loop</div>
            <div class="reactor-events" id="reactorEvents">
              <div class="reactor-event idle">Waiting for events...</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="reactor-handlers">
            <div class="handler-card" id="handlerAccept">
              <span class="handler-icon">🔌</span>
              <span class="handler-name">Accept Handler</span>
            </div>
            <div class="handler-card" id="handlerRead">
              <span class="handler-icon">📖</span>
              <span class="handler-name">Read Handler</span>
            </div>
            <div class="handler-card" id="handlerWrite">
              <span class="handler-icon">✏️</span>
              <span class="handler-name">Write Handler</span>
            </div>
            <div class="handler-card" id="handlerTimer">
              <span class="handler-icon">⏰</span>
              <span class="handler-name">Timer Handler</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="reactor-controls">
          <button class="action-btn primary-btn" id="reactorConnBtn">🔌 New Connection</button>
          <button class="action-btn election-btn" id="reactorDataBtn">📨 Incoming Data</button>
          <button class="action-btn election-btn" id="reactorTimerBtn">⏰ Timer Fires</button>
          <button class="action-btn reset-btn" id="reactorResetBtn">🔄 Reset</button>
        </div>

        <div class="reactor-users">
          <h3>Who Uses This?</h3>
          <div class="users-grid">
            <div class="user-badge"><strong>Redis</strong> — single-threaded event loop, epoll</div>
            <div class="user-badge"><strong>Nginx</strong> — worker processes, epoll + edge-triggered</div>
            <div class="user-badge"><strong>Node.js</strong> — libuv event loop, epoll/kqueue</div>
            <div class="user-badge"><strong>Tokio</strong> — Rust async runtime, epoll/io_uring</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Epoll Event Loop Animation -->
    <section class="detail-section">
      <h2>🎬 epoll Event Loop Animation</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Watch how a single thread handles multiple connections through the epoll event loop cycle.</p>

      <div class="anim-container">
        <div class="anim-timeline" id="animTimeline">
          <!-- rendered by JS -->
        </div>
        <div class="anim-controls">
          <button class="action-btn primary-btn" id="animStartBtn">▶ Start Animation</button>
          <button class="action-btn reset-btn" id="animResetBtn">🔄 Reset</button>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Summary -->
    <section class="explain-section">
      <h2>🏗️ Choosing the Right I/O Model</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Each model has its place. The right choice depends on your concurrency requirements and complexity budget.</p>
      <div class="explain-grid">
        <div class="explain-card">
          <h3>🧵 Blocking I/O</h3>
          <p>
            Best for <strong>low-concurrency</strong> servers (&lt;100 connections) or CLI tools.
            Dead simple to write and debug. Each connection gets its own thread with its own stack.
            Falls apart above ~10K connections due to memory and scheduling overhead.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="explain-card">
          <h3>⚡ epoll</h3>
          <p>
            The <strong>production workhorse</strong>. Handles 100K+ connections on a single thread.
            O(1) for ready notification (unlike poll/select which are O(n)). Edge-triggered mode
            with non-blocking sockets is the gold standard for high-performance servers.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="explain-card highlight-card">
          <h3>💎 io_uring</h3>
          <p>
            The <strong>future of Linux I/O</strong>. Eliminates syscall overhead with shared ring buffers.
            Supports <em>any</em> I/O operation (not just sockets). Kernel-side polling mode
            achieves true zero-syscall I/O. Still maturing but already used in production databases.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="viz-footer">
      <p>Based on <a href="https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/epoll.7.html" target="_blank">epoll(7)</a>, <a href="https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man2/io_uring_enter.2.html" target="_blank">io_uring_enter(2)</a>, and <a href="https://unixism.net/loti/" target="_blank">Lord of the io_uring</a></p>
    </footer>

    <div class="share-buttons">
      <span>Share this visualization:</span>
      <a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=Interactive%20Linux%20I/O%20Models%20visualizer%20—%20blocking%2C%20epoll%2C%20io_uring&url=https://systeminternals.dev/linux/io-models/" target="_blank" class="share-btn">𝕏 Twitter</a>
      <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/sharing/share-offsite/?url=https://systeminternals.dev/linux/io-models/" target="_blank" class="share-btn">in LinkedIn</a>
      <a href="https://news.ycombinator.com/submitlink?u=https://systeminternals.dev/linux/io-models/&t=Interactive%20Linux%20I/O%20Models%20Visualizer" target="_blank" class="share-btn">🟧 Hacker News</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .viz-container {
    max-width: 1100px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .viz-header {
    text-align: center;
    margin-bottom: 40px;
  }

  .viz-header h1 {
    font-size: 2.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, #22c55e, #06b6d4, #8b5cf6);
    -webkit-background-clip: text;
    -webkit-text-fill-color: transparent;
    background-clip: text;
  }

  .subtitle {
    color: #888;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
  }

  h2 {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    color: #fff;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }

  h3 {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    color: #fff;
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }

  .section-desc {
    color: #888;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .section-desc code {
    background: rgba(0,0,0,0.3);
    padding: 2px 6px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: #22c55e;
  }

  /* Overview */
  .overview-section { margin-bottom: 50px; }

  .overview-card {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.1), rgba(139, 92, 246, 0.05));
    border: 1px solid rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.3);
    border-radius: 16px;
    padding: 24px 28px;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: #ccc;
  }

  .overview-card strong { color: #fff; }
  .overview-card em { color: #22c55e; font-style: normal; font-weight: 500; }

  /* Slider */
  .slider-control {
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.03);
    border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1);
    border-radius: 16px;
    padding: 20px 24px;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
  }

  .slider-control label {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: #aaa;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }

  .slider-control label strong { color: #06b6d4; font-size: 1.2rem; }

  .slider {
    width: 100%;
    height: 6px;
    -webkit-appearance: none;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.15);
    border-radius: 3px;
    cursor: pointer;
  }

  .slider::-webkit-slider-thumb {
    -webkit-appearance: none;
    width: 20px;
    height: 20px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: #06b6d4;
    cursor: pointer;
    box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(6,182,212,0.4);
  }

  .slider-marks {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: #666;
    margin-top: 6px;
  }

  /* Compare grid */
  .compare-section { margin-bottom: 50px; }

  .compare-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: 16px;
  }

  .model-card {
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.03);
    border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1);
    border-radius: 16px;
    padding: 20px;
    transition: all 0.3s;
  }

  .model-card h3 {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .model-metric {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
    padding: 6px 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.05);
  }

  .metric-label { font-size: 0.8rem; color: #888; }
  .metric-value { font-size: 0.85rem; color: #06b6d4; font-weight: 600; font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; }

  .model-bar {
    height: 8px;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.08);
    border-radius: 4px;
    margin: 12px 0 8px;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .bar-fill {
    height: 100%;
    border-radius: 4px;
    transition: width 0.5s ease;
  }

  .blocking-fill { background: linear-gradient(90deg, #f59e0b, #ef4444); }
  .epoll-fill { background: linear-gradient(90deg, #06b6d4, #3b82f6); }
  .iouring-fill { background: linear-gradient(90deg, #8b5cf6, #a855f7); }

  .model-verdict {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-align: center;
    padding: 4px;
    border-radius: 6px;
  }

  .model-verdict.good { color: #4ade80; }
  .model-verdict.warning { color: #fbbf24; }
  .model-verdict.danger { color: #ef4444; }
  .model-verdict.excellent { color: #06b6d4; }

  /* Blocking I/O viz */
  .detail-section { margin-bottom: 50px; }

  .blocking-viz {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 24px;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }

  .blocking-server, .blocking-clients {
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.03);
    border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1);
